Does anyone understand their argument clearly?<p>For three flips I get this sample space:<p>TTT no data; TTH no data; THT one data point HT; THH one data point HH;
HTT one data point HT; HTH one data point HT; HHT two data points HH, HT; HHH two data points HH, HH<p>total data points by result:  
HT 4
HH 4<p>For four flips it&#x27;s the same deal, after an H I&#x27;m equally likely to get another H or a T. Of course.<p>What am I missing? I don&#x27;t quite understand their definition of &#x27;empirical probability.&#x27;

It would be trivially easy to support arguments, though. What comes to mind is to send a Hash or Array after a method (represented by a Symbol) that expects/accepts an argument:<p><pre><code>    o.chain :foo, [1, 2, 3], :bar, :baz, {key: &#x27;value&#x27;}

</code></pre>
Here `foo` and `baz` accept arguments, but `bar` does not.<p>Also, it shouldn&#x27;t make any significant performance difference whether this was implemented as a syntactic sugar, an operator or a method (this doesn&#x27;t mean it won&#x27;t perform better than <i>my example method</i>).
